stories: Classical convolutional neural networks (CNNs) have been successfully utilized for image recognition in recent years. Quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNs) are introduced as a new extension of CNNs that leverage quantum mechanisms. These quantum mechanisms enable a more efficient training process in QCNNs by reducing the input size from $n$ to $log_2n. This study implements and compares both CNNs and QCNNs by evaluating losses and prediction accuracy on three popular datasets: MNIST handwritten digits, Fashion MNIST, and cat/dog face images. Additionally, data augmentation (DA), a common technique in CNNs for enhancing classification performance by generating similar images from original inputs, is integrated into QCNNs. Surprisingly, the results indicate that data augmentation did not enhance the performance of QCNNs. The rationale behind this finding is discussed in order to enhance our comprehension of quantum machine learning theory.

Classical convolutional neural networks (CNNs) have been successfully used for image recognition in recent years. Quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNs) are a new extension of CNNs that take advantage of quantum mechanisms. These quantum mechanisms make the training process in QCNNs more efficient by reducing the input size from $n$ to $log_2n. This research implements and compares CNNs and QCNNs by analyzing losses and prediction accuracy on three popular datasets: MNIST handwritten digits, Fashion MNIST, and cat/dog face images. Additionally, data augmentation (DA), a technique in CNNs to improve classification performance by creating similar images from original inputs, is included in QCNNs. Surprisingly, the results show that data augmentation did not improve the performance of QCNNs. The reasoning behind this finding is discussed to enhance our understanding of quantum machine learning theory.

In recent years, Classical convolutional neural networks (CNNs) have been effectively employed for image recognition. Quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNs) are a novel extension of CNNs that capitalize on quantum mechanisms. These quantum mechanisms enhance the training process in QCNNs by decreasing the input size from $n$ to $log_2n. This study conducts a comparison between CNNs and QCNNs through an examination of losses and prediction accuracy using three popular datasets: MNIST handwritten digits, Fashion MNIST, and cat/dog face images. Moreover, data augmentation (DA), a method used in CNNs to enhance classification performance by generating similar images from original inputs, is integrated into QCNNs. Surprisingly, the findings reveal that data augmentation did not boost the performance of QCNNs. The rationale behind this outcome is explored to advance our comprehension of quantum machine learning theory.
